result.execSummary:
The defendant Jeremy D. Livingston was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Contributing to Truancy [Modifiers: PTAC, as a Party to a Crime], a class C misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 948.45(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

ADA Melissa Inlow appeared for the State.  Defendant appeared in person and with Attorney Sebion.  Defendant plead no contest to count 1 in 15CM115.  Count 2 dismissed, but read in for sentencing purposes.  Defendant plead no contest to the charge in 16CM109.   Court recited the charges and possible penalties on the counts he plead to.  Defendant understood.  Court reviewed the plea questionnaire, constitutional rights and elements with the defendant.  Defense stipulated that there is a factual basis for the plea.   Court found that the defendant freely, voluntarily, and intelligently entered his pleas and waived his constitutional rights.  Court found that a factual basis exists for the plea.  Found guilty of Contributing to Truancy contrary to 948.45(1).  1 count each case.  Joint recommendation.  15 days jail.  Concurrent.  CC.  Court ordered:  15 days jail, concurrent. Start on or before 8/20/16 at 6:00 pm. May serve on EMP.    CC.  DNA surcharge on 16CM109.  Pay @ $40/mo starting 9/1.    Court advised defendant of the DNA submission requirement.
